LEPTOSPIROSIS - HONDURAS: (COLON) NOSOCOMIAL SUSPECTED
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 16 Aug 2018
Source: Once Noticias [in Spanish, machine trans., summ., edited]
http://www.oncenoticias.hn/seis-casos-leptospirosis-tocoa/


Authorities of the San Isidro de Tocoa General Hospital, Colón, confirmed 6 cases of leptospirosis in that community.

The authorities of health region number 6 of Colón, called on the population to stay alert to this new threat to health. The hospital spokesman said that 3 of those affected are employees of the health center and underwent surgery. "After having suspicions in these cases, it was confirmed by tests that patients suffered from leptospirosis." The spokesman said.

Leptospirosis is an infection caused by contact with the bacteria _Leptospira_, which is found in fresh water that has been contaminated by the urine of [infected] animals. According to studies at the National Library of Medicine in the United States, leptospirosis does not spread from one person to another, except in very rare cases. Occasionally it is transmitted through sexual contact, breast milk, or from a mother to her fetus. The most likely people to contract it are farmers, farmers, people who live where there is animal husbandry, people who work in sewers. In the case of infections in the home, it is more common among people who have pets such as dogs, domestic livestock, or the presence of infected rodents.

Epidemiologists claim that the center and north of the country present the greatest risk of presenting an outbreak. Areas that are easily flooded or where there is sugarcane production are vulnerable.

[Byline: Leandro Rivera]

