Communicated by
Kathryn Soderholm
<kathryn.soderholm@gmail.com>

[Leptospirosis is spread mainly by contact with fresh, unchlorinated water, or soil that has been contaminated by the urine of infected animals or plants contaminated with infected animal urine. Inhalation of aerosols of contaminated fluids, such as may occur in abattoirs. or ingestion of foods contaminated with urine of infected animals are also occasional modes of transmission. Human-to-human transmission is very rare, but has been documented through sexual intercourse, breastfeeding, and mother to fetus (https://www.cdc.gov/leptospirosis/pdf/fs-leptospirosis-clinicians-eng-508.pdf).

Because humans excrete viable _Leptospira_ in the urine for only a few weeks after the onset of clinical symptoms, and _Leptospira_ are found in blood or CSF for only the first 7-10 days of symptoms, nosocomial transmission to healthcare workers is possible, but unusual; the CDC lists this disease as requiring "standard" type of hospital infection control precautions, although at this site CDC says that leptospirosis is "not transmitted from person to person" (https://www.cdc.gov/infectioncontrol/guidelines/isolation/appendix/type-duration-precautions.html).

We are not told if the 3 hospital employees with leptospirosis in the news report above had patient or clinical laboratory contact that would put them at risk of nosocomial leptospirosis.

Tocoa, with a population of 94 120 in 2015, is a city in the northern Honduran department of Colón slightly inland on the right bank of the Aguán River (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tocoa,_Colón). - Mod.ML

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Tocoa, Colón, Honduras: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5975768,25251]
